        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <add>Hebrew</add>
            </p>
            <p><placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>Sept 13/5613</date> A. M.</p>
            <p><addressee>Revd Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>!</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Though I promised you when I was in your city to<lb/>
                <sic>comunicate</sic> to you, <del>so could I not</del> being not able to comply
                with your<lb/> request, to my regret, owing to a famine of news, I deferred it.<lb/>
                As <sic>agreable</sic> the task would be to me, and as <sic>meagre</sic><lb/> &amp;
                barren even my <sic>comunication</sic> would have been, should I<lb/> have
                    <sic>knowen</sic> something important enough of recording<lb/> in your paper, I
                certainly would have complied with.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Would I have <sic>knowen</sic> that your correspondents here,<lb/>
                would not have informed you, as regards the dedication<lb/> of the synagogue in
                        <placeName><hi rend="underline">Wmsburg</hi></placeName> in its proper time,
                I would<lb/> have taken the liberty of doing so, a I have <sic>wittnesed</sic><lb/>
                the consecration.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">As regards me, I can give you the greatest satisfaction<lb/> of my
                situation. The institution of <persName>Mr Sivor</persName> (the proprie<lb/>tor)
                    <sic>encreases</sic>
                <sic>dayly</sic>. We held yesterday our examination,<lb/> the first since our
                existence (3 months!) which result<lb/> to give, would be immodest from me to
                    <sic>comunicate</sic>;<lb/> as you will hear of it (?!) Some of the gentlemen of
                the<lb/> committee were <persName>Mr Jones</persName> or <persName>Jonas</persName>
                and <persName>Dr Friedlein</persName> (who former<lb/>ly was a <sic>candidat</sic>
                of Rabbinism, and a pedagogue in the<lb/> house of <persName>Mr Lorsh</persName> of
                    <placeName>Munich, Bavaria</placeName>) which we both <del>eminint</del><lb/>
                eminent &amp; high learned gentlemen. The minor class<lb/> I instruct. Also the
                sacred language, to the little sons<lb/> of <persName>Judah</persName>, with the
                translation of the Bible <add>Hebrew</add> &amp; <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> every
                        <date><sic>sunday</sic></date> is my task. I give them, then a lecture
                on</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Judaism, which always <sic>in</sic> followed &amp; repeated, with more<lb/> strength
                by our orthodoxish Proprietor <persName>Mr. Livor</persName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The children some 12 or 13 years old, coming from other<lb/> schools
                to ours are not able of reading hebrew, nor translate<lb/> a chapter of the
                pentateuch correct. I do not com<lb/>prehend, how that is!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">But the skillful Teacher, who without fatiguing
                <sic>know's</sic>,<lb/> how to arrange such labours <sic>displayes</sic> his talents
                of<lb/> showing the Hebrew juveniles, what their future destinat<lb/>ion to what
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName> is chosen &amp; dedicated &amp;c. By some<lb/> of
                children, it had effected already.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">But the most what is to deplore, the moral instruc<lb/>tion the
                child receives in school is all forgotten when<lb/> the child returns home, to the
                parental roof &amp; <sic>wittnessed</sic><lb/> how busily the father is engaged on
                the <date>sabbath</date> in selling<lb/> goods; how the mother stands in the kitchen
                preparing<lb/> food (as I saw on <add>Hebrew</add>)! Such is our Judaism!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I would like very much to occupy your attention a<lb/> little
                longer, but the time of our devotion draws nigh.<lb/> I wish you to the beginning of
                the year, that the<lb/> Lord of all flesh may <sic>grand</sic> you life for many
                years<lb/> to come, to enjoy good health &amp; that the seed which you<lb/>
                <sic>distralated</sic><add>?</add> in your Occident may not by its readers<lb/> fall
                of barren soil; that your toil &amp; labour may<lb/> be blessed
                <add>Hebrew</add>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Please dear Sir! I rejoice me, with your
                    comu,<lb/><sic>nication</sic> and you will oblige yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">brotherly connected in faith</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author">Solomon Weil</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <placeName>No 262 Fifth Street</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <placeName>near Avenue C.</placeName>
            </p>
